            "Move R to divide V"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What specific value does the index 10³ represent in electrical metric prefixes?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "1,000",
            "Kilo",
            "10 multiplied by itself three times"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "Why is it mathematically dangerous to treat an index like 10³ as a simple multiplication of 10 times 3 when calculating electrical values?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "Indices represent powers not simple multiplication",
        "10³ equals 1,000 whereas 10 times 3 only equals 30",
        "It would result in a massive calculation error",
        "Metric prefixes like kilo depend on the power of ten"
      ],
      "hint": "Remember: if it multiplies on the left, it divides on the right. For indices, 10³ means 10 x 10 x 10."
    },
    {
      "title": "Trigonometry and Percentages",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "What is the four-step memory aid used to calculate the hypotenuse of a right-angled triangle using Pythagoras' Theorem?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Square-Square-Sum-Root",
            "Square the two shorter sides",
            "Add the squares together",
            "Take the square root"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "Which memory aid is used to remember the functions for Sine, Cosine, and Tangent?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "SOH CAH TOA",
            "Sine is Opposite over Hypotenuse",
            "Cosine is Adjacent over Hypotenuse",
            "Tangent is Opposite over Adjacent"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What is the correct mathematical method to find a 5% voltage drop from a total voltage value?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Multiply by 0.05",
            "Multiply the base number by the decimal version",
            "Do not just add the percentage figure"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "When calculating the total impedance where resistance and reactance meet at right angles, why must we use the Square-Square-Sum-Root method rather than just adding the two values together?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "The values form the sides of a right-angled triangle",
        "Simple addition does not account for the geometric relationship",
        "The total impedance is represented by the hypotenuse",
        "Pythagoras' Theorem is required for right-angled vectors"
      ],
      "hint": "Use SOH CAH TOA for angles and the \"Square-Square-Sum-Root\" steps for Pythagoras."
    }
  ]
}

